Democracy without people's connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this is happening everywhere in the world.
In some way, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election results is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes cast as "winners."
Von Holland über Finnland bis nach Argentinien und Japan werden Mehrheitsregierungen auf der Grundlage von Minderheiten gebildet.
Auch die scheinbaren Ausnahmen beweisen nicht das Gegenteil.
Nur wenige Amerikanische Präsidenten waren von viel mehr als 10 % der Wahlberechtigten gewählt worden. Tatsächlich hat sich die Hälfte der Wahlberechtigten in den USA nicht einmal zur Teilnahme an der Wahl eingeschrieben; von jenen, die sich haben registrieren lassen, geht die Hälfte nicht wählen; von denen, die abstimmen, stimmt weniger als die Hälfte für den Wahlsieger.
Sogar Tony Blairs "dammbruchartige" Mehrheit in Großbritanniens Unterhaus steht auf wackeligem Füßen: Die Labour-Partei bekam bei der letzten Wahl im Jahr 2002 nur etwas über 40% der Stimmen und das bei einer Wahlbeteiligung von 60 %.
Demnach unterstützten nur 24 % der Gesamtwählerschaft Blairs Partei.
In most countries, the situation in elections looks quite different now than it did twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer is that voters distrust the political parties.
The election democracy functions in most countries based on the mediation of organizations that put forth candidates who support certain packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "campaign program."
For a number of reasons, this long-standing practice no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to pick and choose for themselves.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific convictions.
Such developments have distanced the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays along with the party game anymore.
As a result, the public's suspicion of political parties grows, not least because it is expensive to participate, just like in professional sports.
If the costs are covered by taxpayers, it is taken very badly.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to find channels to obtain money that are often questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last few decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indications - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a parliamentary democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and therefore are not equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, rather independent development comes into play.
People are today more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
Yet, as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they have cast at the voting booth.
Sometimes, they never see the desired results.
The democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful weighing of alternatives.
The consumer as a voter, however, does not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often also effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Dann gibt es noch die Nicht-Regierungsorganisationen. Sie haben oft eine undemokratische Eigenstrukturen, scheinen aber doch noch enger mit den Bürgern verbunden zu sein.
Darüber hinaus gibt es natürlich die Möglichkeit, gänzlich abzuschalten und die Politik den Experten zu überlassen, um sich auf andere Schwerpunkte des Lebens zu konzentrieren.
Letzteres birgt wohl die größten Risiken in sich, weil es den schleichenden Autoritarismus fördert, der ein Zeichen unserer Zeit ist.
Aber auch die anderen Anzeichen der Trennung zwischen Politik und Bürger sorgen für einen recht unsicheren Zustand, weil niemand mehr sagen kann, wie repräsentativ die herrschenden Ansichten sind.
Einige möchten den Knoten durch mehr direkte Demokratie durchschlagen.
But a continuous connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There is still much to be said in favor of holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to reconnect them more closely with the citizens.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could turn out to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and elections and representative governments might once again come to life.
Yet this is probably not sufficient to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who care about the constitution of freedom must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
